{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527716"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:33:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:33:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14218"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14218"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.07,0.16,0.16,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6904"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57029"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6904"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14218"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42479"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1008"},{"type":"tags","id":"1086"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"1845"},{"type":"tags","id":"2918"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15760"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17371"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17442"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17645"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17785"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43505"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57029"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of frothy urine and facial puffiness. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 150/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. JVP is 5cm and the patient has pitting oedema to the groin. Urinalysis reveals 3+ protein without haematuria. Investigations reveal hypoalbuminaemia and serum creatinine 130 \u00b5mol/L (45-90).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis","ANCA-associated vasculitis","Thin basement membrane disease","Anti-glomerular basement membrane disease","Diabetic nephropathy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhilst exact quantification of the degree of proteinuria is necessary, this patient likely presents with nephrotic syndrome. Nephrotic syndrome is characterised by nephrotic range proteinuria (3-3.5g/24hours), hypoalbuminaemia (generally at least moderately severe), oedema and hypercholesterolaemia. Differentials for a patient presenting with relatively sudden onset nephrotic syndrome include minimal change disease, \u003Cstrong\u003Efocal segmental glomerulosclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E and membranous nephropathy. \u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E and amyloidosis can also present as nephrotic syndrome, but generally diabetic nephropathy presents with subnephrotic or nephrotic range proteinuria (as opposed to the complete nephrotic syndrome). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThin basement membrane disease\u003C/strong\u003E does not present with nephrotic syndrome, but rather typically presents with isolated microscopic haematuria. \u003Cstrong\u003EANCA-associated vasculitis\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-glomerular basement membrane\u003C/strong\u003E disease typically present with microscopic haematuria and favour a nephritic syndrome pattern. These latter two conditions can also present as rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis and often warrant urgent diagnosis and management. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nephrotic syndrome is characterised by nephrotic range proteinuria (3-3.5g/24hours), hypoalbuminaemia (generally at least moderately severe), oedema and hypercholesterolaemia"],"references":["Hashmi MS, Pandey J. Nephritic Syndrome. In: StatPearls [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK562240/","Rosenberg AZ, Kopp JB. Focal Segmental Glomerulosclerosis. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2017 Mar 7;12(3):502-517. doi: 10.2215/CJN.05960616. Epub 2017 Feb 27. Erratum in: Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2018 Dec 7;13(12):1889. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5338705/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42479"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14218"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42479"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-24T00:25:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-24T00:26:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6904"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57029"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"d